ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;">A person with =
knowledge of Sephora=E2=80=99s business told me that the retailer=E2=80=99s=
 top fragrance brand =E2=80=9Cby far=E2=80=9D is
Kayali, <em>not</em> the usual number one, Chanel. I=E2=80=99m told that Ka=
yali=E2=80=99s Yum Boujee Marshmallow, which launched in November 2024, had=
 the largest number of pre-signups for any fragrance ever at Sephora. =E2=
=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve been hearing about it internally obsessively,=E2=80=9D =
said an executive who attended the summit.<br/><br/>Kayali=E2=80=99s founde=
r, <strong>Mona Kattan</strong>, also co-founded Huda Beauty with big siste=
r <strong>Huda Kattan</strong>, who in 2024 returned to her position as the=
 makeup label=E2=80=99s C.E.O.
after a tumultuous few years. (Huda Beauty has recently had a comeback, but=
 more on that another time.) Since its inception, Kayali has operated as a =
Huda sub-brand, but a few weeks ago, it was announced that Huda Beauty had =
spun Kayali out into a separate entity, now owned by Mona and General Atlan=
tic, the blue chip P.E. firm. The spinoff was a smart move, considering Kay=
ali did more than $26 million in sales at Sephora in the U.S. last December=
, according to YipitData. And that figure doesn=E2=80=99t
even include the brand=E2=80=99s global direct sales online or Sephora Midd=
le East, where the brand is also <em>hugely</em> popular.<br/><br/>Kayali=
=E2=80=99s Yum franchise=E2=80=94specifically 2023=E2=80=99s Yum Pistachio =
Gelato (you can=E2=80=99t make this shit up)=E2=80=94was the turning point =
in the U.S. market. =E2=80=9CYum Pistachio was a tornado,=E2=80=9D said a p=
erson close to Kayali. Its success completely changed how Kayali approached=
 its U.S. business, and they started specifically packaging certain scents =
as =E2=80=9CU.S. juices.=E2=80=9D For example, Eden Juicy
Apple and Eden Sparkling Lychee were both marketed early on to =E2=80=9Crea=
lly play into the U.S. consumer in a way that would be celebrated and embra=
ced.=E2=80=9D (Also, it helped that one of Kayali=E2=80=99s signature scent=
s, Vanilla 28, happens to be a trendy =E2=80=9Cgourmand.=E2=80=9D)<br/><br/=
>It doesn=E2=80=99t hurt that Kayali is <em>extremely</em> well priced: A g=
iant 100-ml bottle retails for around $130, compared to a Le Labo city scen=
t of the same size that I once paid more than $500 for. I=E2=80=99m certain=
ly not the target customer for
Boujee Marshmallow and Pistachio Gelato, but even I can appreciate the appe=
al. Hopefully, Kayali will keep thriving, General Atlantic will get that bi=
g exit, and the Sephora Brand Summit=E2=80=99s darling can walk away with i=
ts rose=E2=80=A6 at least until next year.</p></div>
